        <h2 id="understanding-localization">
            Understanding localization: more than just translation
        </h2>

        <p>
            Before discussing the importance of localizing content into Russian,
            it is worth first explaining the terminology involved.
        </p>
        <p>
            For some, translation might seem as simple as inputting text into
            Google Translate, resulting in an instant translation. While machine
            translation can indeed accelerate the process and assist with basic
            translations, it often overlooks cultural nuances, making it less
            reliable for nuanced or sensitive content. However, for obtaining a
            general understanding of non-critical texts, this method, followed
            by thorough proofreading and revision by a human, can sometimes be
            adequate.
        </p>
        <p>
            For those requiring professional-grade translation, the process
            involves more than simple text conversion from one language to
            another. It is about transforming a text from a source language into
            a target language while conveying the original meaning as accurately
            as possible. This level of precision is crucial, especially in
            industries where the slightest misinterpretation can lead to
            significant consequences.
        </p>
        <p>
            However, when translating SaaS (Software as a Service) products,
            online tools, platforms that rely on web traffic, web apps,
            websites, online content, and landing pages that target specific
            audiences with commercial intent, mere translation falls short. It
            is not just about changing words from one language to another; you
            want your content to be culturally relevant and resonate deeply with
            your target audience to encourage conversions. This requires
            adapting the entire user experience, not just the text. This is
            where the true value of localization becomes apparent.
        </p>
        <p>
            As you may have guessed, localization encompasses a wider spectrum.
            It includes <a
                href="https://www.getblend.com/blog/localization-vs-translation/"
            >
                a variety of factors</a
            > critical for ensuring your content resonates with a new audience:
        </p>

        <ul>
            <li>control of date and time formats and currency presentation;</li>
            <li>cultural nuances like preferred colors, symbols, and music;</li>
            <li>
                adherence to specific regulations, legal requirements, and
                financial particulars;
            </li>
            <li>
                subtleties in language such as humor, slogans, emotional
                connections, taglines, and customer interactions;
            </li>
            <li>
                understanding of product features and their relevance to the new
                audience;
            </li>
            <li>
                knowledge of prevalent devices, platforms, and social media used
                by the target audience.
            </li>
        </ul>

        <p>Overall, localization includes two key types of adaptation:</p>

        <ul>
            <li>
                Cultural adaptation: This involves more than linguistic changes.
                To truly resonate with the target audience, content must be
                adapted culturally. This includes aligning content with local
                customs, cultural references, societal norms, and even humor.
            </li>
            <li>
                Functional adaptation: In the case of products, especially
                digital ones like software and websites, localization also
                involves adapting functional aspects such as date formats,
                currency, and legal requirements to ensure the product is usable
                in the target region.
            </li>
        </ul>

        <p>
            To summarize, at its core, translation is about transforming text
            from one language to another while preserving the original meaning.
            Localization, however, goes much further. It adapts the entire
            product or content to appear native to a new audience. The scope of
            localization is boundless, reaching well beyond the confines of
            translation.
        </p>

        <p>
            What is remarkable about effective localization is that, when done
            well, it makes a program, website, or mobile app seem as though it
            was tailor-made for the user, creating a seamless experience that
            feels completely natural.
        </p>

        <h2 id="russian-localization-matters">
